item.title: H&M Sales Disappoint But Margin Target on Track
item.description: H&M reported a 6% rise in fiscal third-quarter sales, undershooting forecasts, but said its work toward hitting a 10% operating margin in 2024 was heading in the right direction.

item.title: China's Defense Minister Has Been Removed From Post, U.S. Officials Say
item.description: Chinese Defense Minister Li Shangfu was taken away last week by authorities for questioning, while U.S. officials say he is being removed from his post.

item.title: Corporate Bonds to Benefit From Fall in Inflation, Modest Growth
item.description: The ECB’s confidence that core inflation will continue to ease gives room to some modest economic growth in 2024 and this is supportive for the corporate bond segment, Vontobel said.

item.title: Instacart Set to Raise IPO Price Target After Successful Arm Debut
item.description: At the high end of the new range, the grocery-delivery company would be valued at nearly $10 billion on a fully diluted basis.

item.title: China's Economy Shows Fresh Signs of Fragile Recovery
item.description: Spending in stores and factory production rose in August, and unemployment fell, but the property sector continued to threaten growth.

item.title: UAW Strikes at Plants Owned by GM, Ford, Stellantis
item.description: The walkouts are the first to hit all three automakers at the same time and affect factories in Missouri, Ohio and Michigan.

item.title: EUR/USD's Outlook Still Weak, Charts Show
item.description: Following EUR/USD’s drop below significant support on Thursday, UOB said its bearish stance on the currency pair has been substantiated and the next level to watch is March’s low near 1.0515.

item.title: Russia Seeks to Expand Naval Presence in the Mediterranean
item.description: Moscow has discussed long-term docking rights in ports in eastern Libya with the warlord that controls the area, as it seeks to deepen its influence in Africa.

item.title: Rising Rates Make Big Companies Even Richer
item.description: The Fed raised interest rates to slow the economy—but at some big companies, the moves had the opposite effect, boosting profits and spending power.

item.title: Saudi Arabia Once Banned Videogames. Now, It Wants to Export Them.
item.description: The kingdom is pouring $40 billion into a bid to be a world leader in the industry.

item.title: Chemical Companies Face Awkward Wait for Recovery, Berenberg Says
item.description: Chemical companies likely face a few awkward months as signs of a recovery in the sector take time to emerge, Berenberg said, adding that while auto demand has been strong, there were hints of caution toward the sector as pandemic-era backlogs are depleted.
